<HEAD>
<title>
An Open Memo from Tom Lenard Summarizing PFF's Environmental Roundtable -- 4/21/96
</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000">
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P><br><br>

<P>
<B>Date:</B>March
21, 1996<br>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">To:</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial"> Interested
Partiers </FONT><br>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">From:</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial"> Thomas
Lenard, Senior Fellow and Director of Regulatory Studies</FONT><br>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">RE:</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial"> Summary
of Discussion at March 18, 1996, Environment Roundtable</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There is a general consensus that the environment
has improved significantly over the last quarter century, as a
result of many factors including, but not limited to, government
programs.  The nation has in fact gotten something for the hundreds
of billions of dollars that it spends each year on the environment,
though not as much as it should have.  Our environmental policies
have from the outset been subject to criticism for their reliance
on rigid, command-and-control methods that stifle innovation and
the development of new technologies.  With more flexible, better-designed
policies, we could be getting much greater environmental benefits
and more economic growth at the same time.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In an increasingly dynamic economy, the current
framework of environmental regulation is viewed as an increasingly
burdensome &quot;dinosaur.&quot;  As one of the participants observed,
the dinosaur, full of bones and therefore inflexible, did not
survive.  In contrast, the shark, a contemporary of the dinosaur,
had no bones, only cartilage, and has survived to modern times.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">MESSAGE<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There was widespread agreement at the roundtable
that proponents of change have not developed an effective way
of communicating with a population that is strongly environmentalist.
<BR>
</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">There was also agreement that the message
should focus on our ability to do a better job of providing environmental
benefits and on what a better environment means - not that we
can do it at lower cost.</FONT>
</UL>

<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Similarly, focusing on excessive regulatory
costs and the need to base regulations on good risk and cost-benefit
analysis does not resonate with the public.  In fact, it is likely
that lower costs translates into lower benefits in many people's
minds.</FONT>
</UL>

<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">DEVELOPING A REPLACEMENT<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">A prerequisite to developing a good message
is developing a vision of the direction in which environmental
policy should go, as well as some specific policy proposals. 
<I>Criticizing the existing framework without proposing something
to replace it is not persuasive</I>.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The business community has strongly supported
regulatory reform legislation, which had tough sledding in 1995
because it was proposed in a vision vacuum and was perceived (and
sometimes promoted) as a rollback of existing protections.  In
fact, the payoff to regulatory reform legislation is probably
overstated, because it is based on the assumption that we can
mandate regulation that is well-informed and rational.  This has
never been the case in any regulatory context, and there is no
reason to expect it now.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Rather, <I>the challenge is to establish institutions
that create the right incentives to produce environmental benefits</I>
- but with appropriate incentives to also incorporate other values.
 Environmental policies should be more flexible, focus on outputs
rather than inputs, and rely to a much greater extent on property
rights and market-oriented approaches.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">EXAMPLES<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There was substantial support for devolving
environmental responsibilities to the states, and for the view
that this frequently leads to better decisions, because costs
and benefits are borne by the same population.  A recurring theme
was that the states are more receptive to new ideas and have adopted
them more readily than has the federal government.  For example:
<BR>
</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">North Carolina's Tar-Pimlico River Basin
Association is North America's only operating river association
that brings together point and nonpoint sources of pollution in
a combined trading effort to reduce discharges into a river. 
This approach, which is common elsewhere, is based on property
rights and contracts and was achieved with the support of the
Environmental Defense Fund.  River basin managers monitor outcomes
- the quality of the river - and the responsibility of paying
for damages disciplines polluters.</FONT>
</UL>

<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">The state of Pennsylvania now accepts ISO
14000 certification, which frequently is necessary for trading
in world markets, as a substitute for evidence that firms meet
Pennsylvania standards.</FONT>
</UL>

<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Numerous other examples, not necessarily new,
of ways to provide a better incentive structure were discussed:
<BR>
</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Performance goals should be established
with complete flexibility to meet those goals in the most efficient
manner.  This rewards rather than penalizes innovation.</FONT>
</UL>

<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Auditing programs should provide an incentive
to uncover problems and provide solutions.</FONT>
</UL>

<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Positive incentives should be provided
to landowners for habitat conservation and wildlife protection,
through creation of markets or by bringing the costs of environmental
amenities on-budget.</FONT>
</UL>

<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Finally, we can learn something from the Europeans,
who frequently deal with environmental issues in a less contentious
and litigious fashion than we do here.  For example, the European
system for dealing with abandoned hazardous waste sites is actually
producing results.  Depending on the level of the hazard, sites
are being contained or mitigated, sometimes at public expense,
and returned to appropriate uses.</FONT>
<br>
<br>
<center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center><br>
</blockquote>

</BODY>

</HTML>
