<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Small Business Tax Watch</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<blockquote>
<center>
<P>
<P>
<i>December 1996</i><BR>
<P>
<hr>
<p>
<h2>The Estate Tax: Another Case of Envy Run Amok</h2><BR>
by Raymond J. Keating
<br>
Chief Economist
Small Business Survival Foundation<BR>
</center>
<hr>
<P>
<P>
Envy always makes for dismal economics and bad tax policy.  We've
made this point time and again at the Small Business Survival
Foundation (for example, see &quot;The Great Tax Debate: Making
Sense of Competing Tax Plans by Raymond J. Keating, June 1995).
 Unfortunately, most of today's U.S. tax system can only be justified
on the basis of envy &#173;&#173; sound economics plays no part
at all.
<P>
The income tax, for example, diminishes incentives for working,
saving, investing, and risk taking, while at the same time, is
inefficient and intrusive.  The current U.S. income tax came into
existence in 1913.  It may have seemed fairly innocuous at first.
 Rates ranged from 1 percent to 7 percent, with the lowest rate
not taking effect until a married couple's income hit $60,000
(in inflation&#173;adjusted 1995 dollars, that is) and the top
rate not kicking in until income topped $7.4 million (again, in
1995 dollars).  In subsequent years, as we all know, income tax
rates skyrocketed, reaching ever deeper into the pockets of all
working Americans, not just the wealthy.  And for the most part,
government squandered these resources.
<P>
Following quickly on the heals of the income tax was the estate
tax, imposed in 1916.  This was another envy&#173;driven levy.
 When first imposed, the estate tax was targeted at the rich,
with rates ranging from 1 percent to 10 percent.  Today, the estate
tax takes hold at a lower threshold, with far more severe tax
rates, ranging from 18 percent to 55 percent (even 60 percent
for certain estates).  That is, since the estate tax's inception,
the lowest rate has jumped by 1,700 percent and the top rate by
more than 205 percent.  In addition, the highest tax rate would
have taken hold at an estate valued at almost $70 million under
the original estate tax structure, versus today's, with the top
rate kicking in at just over $3 million.
<P>
Efforts to cut the estate tax are worthy.  However, since no sound
economics basis exists for such a tax, and since the estate tax
serves as a major destroyer of family businesses and jobs, the
most productive step would be to eliminate the estate tax.  
<P>
Envy must give way to economics in order for entrepreneurship
and the economy to flourish.<BR>

<P>
<hr>
<P>
<h3><font color="FFOOOO">Estate Tax in Real Dollars</h3></font>
<P>
<b>Original Estate Tax</b><p>
<u>Rate</u><p>
Lowest Rate	1%<p>
Highest Rate 	10%<p>
<P>
<u>Dollar Level for Tax Rate to take Hold</u><p>
Lowest Rate $50,000<p>
Highest Rate $5,000,000<p>
<p>
<u>Original Estate Tax Rate Rate to Take Hold in 1995 Dollars</u><p>
Lowest Rate     $694,444<p>
Highest Rate   $69,444,444<p>
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<b>1995 Estate Tax</b><p>
<u>Rate</u><p>
Lowest Rate	18%<p>
Highest Rate 	55%<p>
<p>
<u>Dollar Level for Tax Rate to Take Hold</u><p>
Lowest Rate	$600,000<p>
Highest Rate	$3,040,000<p> 
<P>
<hr>
* An additional 5 percent surcharge tax is levied on estates of
values between $10 million and $21 million, raising the top rate
to 60 percent.
<P>
Source for tax rates: &quot;The Case for Repealing the Estate
Tax&quot; by William W. Beach, The Heritage Foundation Backgrounder,
August 21, 1996.  Calculations by author.
<P>
<BR>
<p>
<center> [ <a href="/sbsc/">SBSC Home</a> | <a href="/sbsc/i-tax.html">Tax Watch Index</a> ] </center>
<p><br>
</blockquote>
