ific issues led by nationally-recognized  scholars and thinkers. Past forums have included &quot;Economics and the  Judeo-Christian Tradition,&quot; with George Gilder, author of <I>Wealth  and Poverty, Men and Marriage</I> and other books; &quot;Church, State,  and the Law,&quot; with former Attorney General Edwin Meese; &quot;Religion  and International Affairs,&quot; with George Weigel, past President of  the Ethics and Public Policy Center; &quot;Academic Freedom and the Refutation  of Scientific Naturalism,&quot; with Stephen Meyer, Director of Discovery  Institute's Center for the Renewal of Science and Culture; &quot;Religion,  Free Speech, and the Equal Access Act,&quot; with Edward Larson, Professor  of History and Law at the University of Georgia; &quot;The Old Testament  and Politics,&quot; led by Rabbi Daniel Lapin, President of Toward Tradition;  and &quot;God and Culture in the Twenty-First Century,&quot; with Phillip  Johnson of the University of California at Berkeley and Father Robert Sirico  of the Acton Institute.<BR>  <BR>  Each Fellow will also be required to write a 10-15 page essay analyzing  some public issue involving the intersection between religion and public  affairs. A draft of the essay is due by June 23. Fellows will discuss and  revise their essays during their time in Seattle.<BR>  </FONT><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>  <BLOCKQUOTE>    <P><B><FONT COLOR="#99050E" SIZE=+1>Admission Requirements:</FONT></B><FONT     COLOR="#99050E" SIZE=+1> Applicants must be currently enrolled undergraduates    at the junior or senior levels, or graduate students in the first two years    of graduate or law school, or recent college graduates who seek careers    in public life. Required application materials include a copy of the applicant's    academic transcript, two letters of recommendation, a writing sample, and    short statements describing the applicant's career plans and his or her    proposed topic for the essay. <BR>    <BR>    <B>Room, Board, and Travel Costs:</B> In addition to the fellowship of    $1,000, Fellows will be reimbursed up to $400 for travel costs to Seattle.    Fellows will also be provided with lodging, course materials, and some    meals.<BR>    <BR>    <B>Application Deadline:</B> Applications will be accepted until <B><I><TT>April    11, 1997</TT></I></B>, but applications received by March 28 may receive    priority consideration.</FONT></P>  </BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><B><FONT COLOR="#000000" SIZE=+1>If you have questions, would like more  information, or would like to receive an applicaiton form please e-mail  Marshall Sana at </FONT><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="mailto:msana@discovery.org">msana@discovery.org</A></FONT><FONT   COLOR="#000000" SIZE=+1>.</FONT></B></P>  <BLOCKQUOTE>    <P><CENTER><HR></CENTER></P>  </BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE><H1><CENTER><A HREF="aboutdis.html"><IMG SRC="aboutdis.gif" WIDTH="107"HEIGHT="46" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><A HREF="current.html"><IMG SRC="image45.gif" WIDTH="106" HEIGHT="46" ALIGN="MIDDLE" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><AHREF="front.html"><IMG SRC="image46.gif" WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="46" ALIGN="MIDDLE"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><BR><A HREF="ggindex.html"><IMG SRC="image47.gif" WIDTH="109" HEIGHT="48" ALIGN="MIDDLE" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><A HREF="crsc.html"><IMG SRC="crscbttn.gif"WIDTH="105" HEIGHT="48" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><A HREF="whatsnew.html"><IMG SRC="image49.gif" WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="48" ALIGN="MIDDLE"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></CENTER></H1><H3><CENTER><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="image51.gif" WIDTH="147" HEIGHT="59" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A></CENTER></H3><BLOCKQUOTE>  <BLOCKQUOTE>    <P><CENTER><B><FONT COLOR="#000000" SIZE=-1>The George Washington Fellows    Program is sponsored by </FONT><FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="index.html">Discovery    Institute</A></FONT><FONT COLOR="#000000" SIZE=-1>, a non-partisan national    public policy center based in Seattle. </FONT