Clinton health policies.
<P>In 1994, major corporations also gave to the 
Environmental Defense Fund, National Audubon Society, 
Natural Resources Defense Council, and World Wildlife Fund. 
 These groups supported the Administration's ill-fated 
BTU tax on energy the year before.  The tax would have 
increased the price of oil by an estimated 17 percent, coal 
by 15 percent, and natural gas by 11 percent.  But 
apparently many corporations were not outraged by the effort to 
raise taxes and force a reduction in the use of fuel.  In 1994, 
even President Clinton momentarily admitted, &quot;I raised 
your taxes too much.&quot;  Did corporations agree?
<P>When corporations contribute to political advocacy groups that 
want more government programs, they make their own shareholders foot 
the bill twice overas shareholders and as taxpayers.<BR>
 disguise their current policy activism.
<P>In other cases, corporations may distribute 
relatively small contributions as tribute money to buy time and 
avoid harassment.  But the activities of advocacy groups 
during the Clinton years make a mockery of that hope.  
The millions of dollars these groups receive from 
corporations simply enable them to pursue goals that undermine the 
free-enterprise system on which corporations depend.
<P>Of course, some corporations may conclude that 
their well-being ultimately depends on the favor of the 
Administration in power.  That might explain an initial flurry 
of 1993 contributions to the Children's Defense Fund 
and Planned Parenthood.  But this kind of giving yields 
bad public policy and worse philanthropy.
<P>When corporations support advocacy groups that 
want more government entitlements and social services, 
they hurt the recipients of charity as well as charities themselves. 
 This is the sorry lesson of our welfare programs.  
Philanthropy, including corporate philanthropy, should call 
on the desire of good people to do good deeds.  But 
when corporations contribute to political advocacy groups 
that want more government programs, they make their 
own shareholders foot the bill twice overas shareholders 
and as taxpayers.<BR>
<B>Corporate Misgiving</B>
<P>This year's <I>Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy 
</I>contains other examples of foolish giving:
<P>nACORN (the Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now) is a direct-action advocacy group.  
It uses the threat of federal penalties to pressure 
banks, insurance companies, and other financial institutions 
to make higher-risk loans at lower-risk rates to borrowers 
it recommends.  In 1994, BankAmerica, Bank of 
Boston, Chase Manhattan, Fannie Mae, PNC Bank, and the St. 
Paul Companies contributed $483,000 to ACORN.  This is 
an almost six-fold increase in 1993 corporate support 
for ACORN.
<P>nFord Motor Company gave $1,000 to the American Lung Association (ALA), which has lobbied to 
increase EPA emissions standards for automobiles.  ALA's image 
as a non-political public-health group belies its 
aggressive lobbying on a wide range of controversial issues.  Ford 
also donated $10,000 to the World Wildlife Fund, which 
promoted the failed BTU tax to cut fuel consumption 
and increase costs.  What was Ford thinking?
<P>nOil companies Chevron (despite a number two 
rating in our Top Ten) and Atlantic Richfield (ARCO) gave to 
the National Audubon Society and the Center for Marine 
Conservation, both of which oppose offshore oil drilling.  
Chevron, although it gave to groups that support free 
markets, also supported the Trust for Public Lands, which 
also opposes offshore oil drilling.
<P>
<P><B>Harming Charities and Those They Serve</B>
<P>Why do corporations support policy groups whose 
goals are bad for business?  CEOs and managers of 
corporate grantmaking departments may simply be ignorant of 
the agendas of nonprofits applying to them for grants.  
Groups with catchy names and smooth fundraisers often present 
an image at odds with the hardball politics they play in 
Washington.  Large and well-known groups like the 
American Cancer Society, National Audubon Society, and 
Humane Society of the United States trade on their reputations to<BR>
<I>Permission to reprint is granted provided credit is 
given to Capital Research Center.</I><BR>
<B>Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy,</B>
<P>Tenth Edition
<P>with a preface by T.J. Rodgers,
<P>CEO Cypress Semiconductor Corporation
<P>$25.00<BR>
Visa, Mastercard, and American Express orders accepted.  Call (202) 393-2600.  Or send a 
$25.00 check to Capital Research Center, 727 15th 
Street, NW, Suite 800, Washington, DC 20005.
<!-- Generation of story text from PM publication page 10 -->

<BR>
John M. Hood's <I>The Heroic Enterprise</I><BR>
<B>Reviewed by Martin Morse Wooster</B>
<P>What should business' responsibilities be towards 
the community?  Advocates of &quot;corporate social 
responsibility&quot; argue that businesses should use their profits 
&quot;responsibly,&quot; by which they usually mean making donations 
to liberal causes and organizations.
<P>John Hood, president of the John Locke Foundation, 
a market-oriented think tank in Raleigh, North Carolina, 
has a different view.  In <I>The Heroic Enterprise: Business 
and the Common Good</I> (New York: Free Press, 199 
pages, $25.00), he argues that the primary responsibility of 
businesses is not to promote social causes or redistribute 
wealth but, quite simply, to provide needed goods at a 
competitive price.
<P>Take the case of Jerome Lemelson, an inventor 
and philanthropist.  Lemelson has made substantial 
donations to the Smithsonian Institution and the Massachusetts 
Institute of Technology, which co-sponsors the annual 
$300,000 Lemelson-MIT Prize for the best American inventor.  
When Lemelson dies, his foundation will have an endowment 
of at least $300,000,000.
<P>But Hood argues that Lemelson should not be 
celebrated primarily for his philanthropy, but for the five 
hundred inventions he has patented.  These include improvements 
in bar code readers, devices that make assembly lines 
more flexible, and the typewriter tape eraser, which 
Lemelson invented in college.  These, Hood argues, are 
Lemelson's main contribution to society.  &quot;No matter how hard he 
tries, there is no possible way that he can give enough 
money away to make his charitable contribution to society 
equal the value of his contributions as an innovator and 
entrepreneur.&quot;
<P>Advocates of corporate social responsibility often 
judge businesses by looking at how much they give.  But 
Hood suggests that a more meaningful criterion is to 
examine whether the goods and services companies produce 
make people's lives better.  Ben and Jerry's Ice Cream, 
for example, is renowned by some because it gives 7.5 
percent of its profits to charityfar higher than the average 
corporate gift of one percent.  But its profits come from ice 
cream that, although tasty, is loaded with fat.  Who does 
more good for society, Hood asks: Ben and Jerry's or a 
lower-profile company that makes 55-gallon drums which 
ensure that goods can be transported cheaply, ensuring 
lower prices for everyone?
<P>Hood believes that corporations should practice 
&quot;strategic philanthropy;&quot; that is, they should make grants to 
causes <BR>
Terrence Scanlon, Publisher<BR>
Capital Research Center is a nonpartisan education and research organization
<P>classified by the IRS as a 501(c)(3) public charity.<BR>
CRC, 727 15th Street, NW, Suite 800, Washington, DC, 20005 (202) 393-2600  http://www.capitalresearch.org<BR>
that advance a company's interests.  He agrees with 
Sunmark Capital president Menlo Smith, who has said, &quot;because 
our shareholders will always have different charitable 
interests, we concluded long ago that any giving done by 
Sunmark should have a very direct business purpose, and that if 
it does not, the giving should be done individually by 
the shareholders, and not the corporation.&quot;
<P>According to Hood, corporations can practice 
strategic philanthropy in different ways.  Amoco, which has 
long sought a better-educated workforce, has a substantial 
share of its filling stations in urban areas.  Thus, its 
foundation gives mostly to groups seeking to improve education and 
to rebuild inner cities.  Other companies practice 
&quot;cause-related marketing&quot; by making grants in proportion to 
their sales volume.  American Express pioneered this 
approach in 1981 by donating a percentage of the charges made on 
its credit cards to arts organizations in the San Francisco area. 
 It has since launched several national philanthropic 
campaigns, including a 1983 promotion in which a penny 
of every charge was used to help restore the Statue of Liberty. 
 By tying the use of its credit cards to charity, 
American Express has increased card use by 20 percent.
<P>Many corporations also use philanthropy as a means 
to improve employee morale.  General Electric, Questar 
Corp., and Union Planters National Bank encourage employees 
to volunteer at charities in the evenings and on weekends. 
 Researchers at Columbia University and the 
Conference Board have found that such volunteering increases 
workplace productivity.
<P>Hood suggests that one way businesses can improve 
their philanthropy is by supporting organizations that 
promote free enterprise.  Yet he cites data from the Capital 
Research Center showing that many large corporations give 
generously to groups hostile to free markets and limited 
government.  He speculates that corporate giving officers may 
do so to buy off antagonistic anti-business organizations.
<P>This approach, Hood argues, is ineffective.  In the 
long run, companies that support such groups, or that 
make contributions without a clear strategy, are eclipsed in 
the marketplace by competitors that practice strategic 
philanthropy.  Moreover, Hood suggests that advocates of 
corporate social responsibility must recognize that markets 
are not evil, but necessary if businesses are to create the 
wealth that makes philanthropy possible.  &quot;Without an 
efficient market system, there are likely to be more social 
problems (stemming from poverty and technological 
backwardness) on which philanthropists must spend their time and money.&quot;<BR>
D.T. Oliver, Editor
</BODY>
