<html>
<head>
<title>Letter to Congress from Jeane Kirkpatrick on SDI-ABM</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
June 13, 1995
<br>
<br>
<p>
<p>
Dear Member of Congress:
<p>
The overriding issue in defense policy for our times is the capacity of America to defend itself.  For most of our history, what George Washington described as "our blessed location" made us invulnerable to attack by hostile nations.  We are no longer invulnerable and we are presently without the capacity to defend ourselves against ballistic missiles.
<p>
Today, rogue nations are determined to build weapons of mass destruction and acquire ballistic missile technology which will permit these weapons to be delivered over long distances.  Most Americans do not yet understand our vulnerability to such attacks.  Most Americans do not yet understand that for the first time in our history, when we speak of defense matters, we should be talking about our capacity to defend our territory.
<p>
The Dellums and Spratt amendments to H.R. 1530 are completely inadequate, very shortsighted and extremely outdated.  Neither is worthy of your support.  The one proposes to economize where economy is the least appropriate.  The Dellums cuts will cripple the development of national defense systems.  The other sacrifices American security in a vain effort to preserve the ABM Treaty.  The ABM Treaty, designed for a bipolar world, always had dubious value.  It is now wholly outdated.  It's only relevance to the contemporary world is to hamper an effective effort to defend America.
<p>
The development of missile defenses today is technologically and economically feasible.  We can speak and act with confidence in the world only when we have the capacity to defend ourselves and our adversaries understand this.  It is time for the United States to defend the American people.
<p>
Sincerely,<p>
<br>
Jack Kemp<br>
Jeane Kirkpatrick
<p>
<br>
[ <a href="i-ps-lc.html">Letters to Congress</a> | <a href="welcome.html">Home</a> ]
</body>
</html>
