<HTML>
<TITLE>1994 Annual Report - President's Message -- Heritage</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2><I><FONT SIZE = "+3">P</FONT>resident's <FONT SIZE = "+3">M</FONT>essage</I></H2></CENTER>

<CENTER><B>Wow, What a Year!</B></CENTER>
<P>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 30%>
<p>
Early on the morning of November 9, 1994, as I sat contemplating the "tsunami," 
or shock wave, that the national elections had unleashed on official Washington, 
I noticed a copy of "<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/imp.html">The Imperial Congress</a>" in my bookcase, a book which Heritage 
published in 1988.
<P>
In the Foreword to that book, a young Georgia Congressman wrote, "Every citizen 
should be concerned about the arrogance and corruption of the present day Congress. 
 At stake is the liberty of the American public. must reform Congress to make 
it truly representative once again."
<P>
Newt Gingrich had it right. And on Nov. 8, millions of Americans expressed 
that concern at the ballot box by sending to Washington and the statehouses 
and legislatures of America an army of lawmakers dedicated to reforming Congress 
and finishing the conservative revolution Ronald Reagan began in 1980.
<P>
The following week, at the largest President's Club meeting in Heritage's history, 
that same Georgia Congressman gave one of his first public addresses as the 
future Speaker of  the U.S. House of Representatives - the first Republican 
speaker in 40 years. "Heritage," Gingrich said, "is without question the most 
far-reaching conservative organization in the country in the war of  ideas, 
and one which has had a tremendous impact not just in Washington, but literally 
across the planet."
<P>

California Gov. Pete Wilson, three days later, also visited us at Heritage, 
giving a major national address on the ways in which liberalism had distorted 
the relationship between the state and federal governments. Governor Wilson, 
who had spoken earlier in the year at a meeting of our Governors' Forum,  described 
Heritage "as an island of clear thinking and common sense amid the fuzzy-headed 
liberalism of Washington.  Here at Heritage you have long been champions of 
the idea of limited government in order to expand individual opportunity, an 
idea that was at the heart of last week's ballot box rebellion."
<P>
The impact of all this really hit home a week later when Harvard's Kennedy 
School of Government canceled the orientation program it had been holding for 
newly elected members of Congress since 1972. The reason?  Lack of interest: 
Most members of Congress's Class of 1994 had decided to attend the Heritage 
Foundation/Empower America orientation conference. As Harvard's hometown newspaper, 
the liberal Boston Globe, said in a major article, "In the capricious business 
of supplying politicians with academic expertise and advice, if Harvard's star 
is fading, The Heritage Foundation's is surely on the ascent."
<P>

<p>
What a month November was. What a year!

<P>
The important thing to remember is that all of this didn't just happen.  Just 
as Heritage drew up the battle plan for the first conservative insurgency against 
Washington's liberal fortress with our "<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/mnd2.html">Mandate for Leadership</a>" series, we 
also have had a major role in fashioning the new conservative agenda.  Heritage 
welcomed 1994 with "<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/issu.html">Issues '94</a>," first-of-its-kind briefing book for congressional 
candidates. "Issues '94" provided comprehensive data on a dozen key national 
issues, from federal spending and defense policy to congressional reform.
<P>
Later in the year our analysts were asked for their input on the House GOP 
leadership's proposal to do the unthinkable: tell the American voters where 
they stand on the important issues of the day. The result was the "Contract 
with America." 
<P>
This was followed by still another major set of recommendations for the the 
conservative 104th Congress, "The New Member's Guide to the Issues."
<P>
As New York's Village Voice, one of the bellwethers of counterculture liberalism, 
said of the new conservative agenda: "The driving force behind this conservative 
program is the Heritage Foundation, which over the last decade has occupied 
center stage as the preeminent think tank in Washington .... Heritage was the 
architect of the attack on the New Deal Congress, and has been an important 
force in developing the assault on the liberal-minded federal civil service, 
the drive for privatization, and the overall philosophy of free market economics."
<P>

<P>
All of this was accomplished as the men and women of Heritage went about a 
range of activities that made 1994 the single most productive year in our 21-year 
history. We developed "<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/indx.html">The Index of Economic Freedom</a>," which already is redefining 
the U.S. foreign aid debate; produced a comprehensive tax-relief and deficit-reduction 
plan, "Putting Families First," which became the official alternative budget 
of congressional Republicans in 1994; provided much of the intellectual ammunition 
that led to the demise of health-care "reforms" that would have put the federal 
government in charge of the trillion-dollar U.S. health-care system; played 
a major role in the GATT debate; exposed the crime bill as little more than 
another pork-laden social-spending bill; crafted a welfare reform plan that 
would truly "end welfare as we know it"; began work on a major study of agriculture 
policy, with publication timed for the 1995 debate on the farm bill; and launched 
a new institution-wide program, the American Trader Initiative, to push for 
a liberalized trade policy that dramatically increases international business 
opportunities.          
<P>

Clearly, 1994 was a banner year in terms of  policy development. But there 
was much more:
<P>
... Heritage military analysts, in a series of studies examining the administration's 
defense budget, found that the administration had underfunded its own defense 
plan more than $100 billion over five years.
<P>
... Distinguished Fellow <a href="/heritage/staff/bennett.htm">William J. Bennett</a>, one of the country's leading voices 
on cultural policy and a  featured speaker at our April Board Meeting & Public 
Policy Seminar, saw his "The Book of Virtues" stay at the top of the national 
bestseller lists. Touchstone Books, meanwhile, published an expanded and updated 
version of Bennett's landmark Heritage study, "The Index of Leading Cultural 
Indicators." 
<P>
... A seminal study by Heritage Senior Policy Analyst <a href="/heritage/staff/fagan.htm">Patrick Fagan</a>, chronicling 
the terrible consequences to children and society of out-of-wedlock births, 
sent shockwaves across the country, adding a new sense of urgency to the continuing 
debate over welfare reform.
<P>
... We also released the second edition of "<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/safe.html">A Safe and Prosperous America</a>," 
which remains the only comprehensive conservative blueprint for post-Cold War 
foreign and defense policy.
<P>
... The Washington Roundtable for the Asia-Pacific Press (WRAPP) was re-established 
under Heritage's sponsorship; and
<P>
... A record 130 organizations joined us at Heritage's 17th Annual <a href="/heritage/resource_bank/rtoc.html">Resource 
Bank</a> Meeting.
<P>
Major advances in our computer capabilities, meanwhile, provided Heritage analysts 
with a powerful new analytical tool rivaling that of the government itself. 
For example: Using our computer model, Heritage analysts were able to measure 
the impact of health-care proposals on businesses, workers, families, and the 
states.
<P>
In addition to the vastly expanded computer capabilities, we also upgraded 
our radio broadcast facilities, enabling talk show hosts to air their programs 
live from Heritage's studios on Capitol Hill. And our magazine, <a href="/heritage/p_review/welcome.html">Policy Review</a>, 
continued to grow, reaching another circulation milestone - 30,000. As Boston 
Globe columnist David Warsh wrote, "No magazine has been more vivid in conveying 
the cultural breadth and depth of the conservative imagination."
<P>
These are just a few of the highlights from an incredibly productive, whirlwind 
year. Heritage also remained one of Washington's leading policy forums, with 
dozens of  lectures, seminars, and debates filling our Lehrman Auditorium and 
Van Andel Conference Center. 


<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">P</FONT>eople <FONT SIZE = "+2">A</FONT>re <FONT SIZE = "+2">P</FONT>olicy</CENTER></H3>
<P>
As you know, when The Heritage Foundation was first established in 1973 we 
made a conscious decision to be different from Washington's other "think tanks." 
 Our goal - then, as now - was to have an impact on the national public policy 
debate, not just publish research papers and host conferences. To do this, 
we identified target markets in the Congress, the administration, and the news 
media and then designed our research product to meet the needs of the marketplace. 

<P>
Today we are a permanent Washington institution. But we still pride ourselves 
on our originality and inventiveness; on steering the debate, not just responding 
to it. 
<P>
What enables us to do this?  Our people - who are among the chief intellectual 
resources of Washington's new conservative establishment.
<P>
During 1994, we made several important changes in our management team. <a href="/heritage/staff/gaynerl.htm">Lew 
Gayner</a> was named Vice President for External Relations and will oversee Heritage's 
outreach to the business community, conservative policy organizations, and 
the nation's governors. <a href="/heritage/staff/przystup.htm">James Przystup</a>, a former Defense Department official 
and a Japan specialist, was named Director of our Asian Studies Center. Bridget 
Wagner, a 13-year Heritage veteran, was named Director of Business Relations. 
And Margaret Bonilla, a seven-year Heritage veteran, was named Director of 
Development.
<P>
Notable staff additions included <a href="/heritage/staff/fagan.htm">Patrick Fagan</a>, Deputy Assistant Secretary 
of Health and Human Services during the Bush administration, who was named 
Senior Policy Analyst, and <a href="/heritage/staff/winston.htm">David Winston</a>, who joined us as Senior Fellow in 
Statistical Policy Analysis.  
<P>
With sadness we note the passing of three giants of the conservative movement: 
Dr. Russell Kirk, a long-time Heritage Distinguished Scholar, lecturer, critic, 
conscience of the conservative movement, and author of dozens of books,  including 
"The Conservative Mind"; Dr. Walter Judd, conservative leader, American patriot, 
recipient of the Presidential Medal of Freedom, and a dedicated member of The 
Heritage Foundation; and Shelby Cullom Davis, the New York investment banker 
and former Ambassador to Switzerland who served with great distinction as Heritage's 
long-time Board Chairman. The memory of these three great Americans will live 
on at Heritage, as will the impact they had on America and the world.
<P>
While we continue to take great pride in our work, we realize that it is possible 
only because of the continued generous support of our donors. We thank them, 
sincerely. In 1994, income topped $25.5 million, most of it coming from the 
200,000 individuals, foundations, and businesses that comprise the Heritage 
family.
<P>


<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">T</FONT>he <FONT SIZE = "+2>F</FONT>uture</H3></CENTER>
<P>
What about 1995 and beyond? Conservatives have spent the past 20 years building 
a broad network of institutions dedicated to common-sense government  - think 
tanks, state-based research organizations, public interest law groups, radio 
talk shows, on-line computer networks, even a conservative television network 
(soon to be joined by one or more others).  With these institutions solidly 
in place we got our message out. It was heard and understood. 
<P>
Heritage will play a very active role in shaping the new Washington. Our agenda 
 includes reductions in taxes and federal spending - including the elimination 
of several government departments, agencies, programs, and functions - welfare 
and entitlement reform, a revival of federalism, de-regulation of the economy, 
restoring defense readiness, protecting the United States against possible 
missile attack, stopping the spread of global terrorism, and re-examining U.S. 
foreign aid. 
<P>
We are starting an exciting journey that should result in a major change in 
the relationship between the American people and their government. All of us 
at Heritage look forward to being a part of this promising new chapter in American 
history.
<P>
<a href="/heritage/staff/feulner.html">Edwin J. Feulner Jr.</a><br>
<I>President</i>

<BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER></BODY>
