<HTML>
<TITLE>1994 Annual Report - Membership -- Heritage</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2><I><FONT SIZE = "+3">M</FONT>embership</I></H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>America's Most Broadly Supported Think Tank</B></CENTER><P>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 30%>
<p>
<a href="/heritage/dept_writeups/mbrship.html">Join the Heritage
Foundation!</a>
<p>
The Heritage Foundation received another vote of confidence from its members 
and donors in 1994:  For the 21st consecutive year, income from contributions 
was up - to an all-time record of $21.5 million - as was Heritage's influence 
and impact.
<p>
With more than 200,000 individual, foundation, and corporate supporters, The 
Heritage Foundation remains the most broadly supported research institute in 
the United States. Of the $25.5 million in total income - a 12 percent increase 
over 1993 ($22.9 million) - 50 percent was provided by individuals, 25 percent 
by foundations, and 9 percent by business contributors.
<P>
But Heritage members and supporters do more than write checks: They receive 
Heritage publications, attend meetings, visit with Heritage representatives, 
and learn about the issues of the day. Heritage's members fuel the institution's 
success in two ways: They provide the financial resources needed for Heritage 
to do its job in Washington, and many of them take the knowledge they gain 
through their personal involvement with Heritage back to their local communities.
<P>


Since its founding in 1973, Heritage has made it a firm policy to accept no 
government funding, perform no contract work, and maintain no political or 
academic affiliations. All contributions are voluntary and tax deductible under 
Section 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code. This enables Heritage to maintain 
its independence; it also means that Heritage's officers and staff must earn 
the trust of members and supporters each year.
<P>

Most Heritage donors are motivated by two things: They agree with the conservative 
principles upon which Heritage's work is based, and they believe The Heritage 
Foundation uses their money wisely. Said one President's Club member, "If it 
weren't for ... The Heritage Foundation, I would despair for our country. You 
give me a reason for optimism." Added a corporate Executive Committee Member, 
"The Heritage Foundation has earned a reputation as an incubator of ideas ... 
[that] foster democracy, free enterprise and political freedom. We remain convinced 
that there are ample returns on our investment in Heritage and believe the 
important work of The Heritage Foundation needs to continue." And a Heritage 
Associate put it this way: "As our government becomes more oppressive and as 
our culture deteriorates look increasingly to Heritage for solutions. Keep 
up the good work."
<P>
Heritage strives to involve its supporters in the war of ideas in a number 
of ways.  During 1994, the Heritage staff held more than 400 one-on-one meetings 
with individual, foundation, and corporate donors to hear their views and to 
report on Heritage accomplishments. Heritage publications provide another avenue 
of communications. Heritage Members News, published quarterly, is distributed 
to all  200,000 members; members of the President's Club, Associates, and Founder-level 
donors also receive Heritage studies. Regular programs and events for donors 
featuring presentations by policymakers and Heritage experts include the following:

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">F</FONT>ounders</H3></CENTER>

Heritage Founders are those individuals, foundations, and corporations who 
provide $100,000 or more during the year to The Heritage Foundation.  In 1994, 
30 donors gave at the Founders level. Founders are invited to the Annual Board 
Meeting and Public Policy Seminar and to a special Founders briefing at Heritage. 
Those who attended the 1994 briefing, held on  December 7, were able to talk 
shop with Heritage Distinguished Fellow <a href="/heritage/staff/bennett.htm">William Bennett</a>; William Kristol, Chairman 
of the Project for the Republican Future; Vin Weber, Vice Chairman of Empower 
America; and Michael Joyce, President of the Lynde and Harry Bradley Foundation.
<P>


<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">H</FONT>eritage <FONT SIZE = "+2">A</FONT>ssociates</H3></CENTER>

Heritage Associates, those who give $10,000 or more, are invited, along with 
Heritage Trustees and Founders, to participate in Heritage's Annual  Board 
Meeting and Public Policy Seminar. The 1994 meeting, the ninth in this series, 
was held in Amelia Island, FL, in April. Featured speakers were Distinguished 
Fellows William Bennett and <a href="/heritage/staff/kemp.htm">Jack Kemp</a>, Jersey City Mayor Bret Schundler, author 
and Heritage Trustee Midge Decter, and author Charles Murray. Rep. Tillie Fowler 
(R-FL), who represents the northeastern Florida district in which Amelia Island 
lies, welcomed the more than 150 guests.

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">T</FONT>he <FONT SIZE = "+2">P</FONT>resident's 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">C</FONT>lub</H3></CENTER>

With the future Speaker of the House, Newt Gingrich, as the lead-off speaker, 
the Nov. 15 President's Club meeting was the largest in the program's 12-year 
history. The day-long event attracted more than 500 Heritage friends and supporters 
for a series of discussions on Washington's political reordering. In his speech, 
"What the Elections Mean to Conservatives," Gingrich said, "There are changes 
we have to make, and we badly need The Heritage Foundation's help intellectually 
in understanding how to make them." Dinner speaker Jack Kemp focused on Heritage's 
pivotal role as the idea factory for the conservative revolution.
<P>

Representative Gingrich also was the keynote speaker at Heritage's May President's 
Club meeting. Other speakers at the meeting included Rep. Tim Hutchinson (R-AR) 
and, at the Executive Committee luncheon, Rep. Jennifer Dunn (R-WA).

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">P</FONT>hysician's <FONT SIZE = "+2">C</FONT>ouncil</H3></CENTER>

Health care issues dominated public policy in 1994.  With many medical doctors 
feeling excluded from the health-care debate, Heritage Chairman David R. Brown, 
M.D.,  started the Physician's Council. The inaugural meeting, in June, featured 
Sens. Don Nickles (R-OK) and Connie Mack (R-FL), co-sponsors of the Consumer 
Choice Health Security Act, and Bernadine Healy, former Director of the National 
Institutes of Health.  A second meeting of the Physician's Council was held 
in conjunction with the November President's Club meeting.  Nearly 700 doctors 
had joined the Council by year end.

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">R</FONT>egional <FONT SIZE = "+2">P</FONT>olicy 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">S</FONT>eminars</H3></CENTER>

Issues and ideas also were on the agenda at two regional policy seminars held 
in 1994: July 18 in Monterey, CA, where Jack Kemp's keynote address focused 
on the need to make U.S. interests the centerpiece of American foreign policy, 
and March 8 in Palm Beach, FL, where the focus was health care and crime.
<P>

<P>

In addition to these two half-day regional meetings, Distinguished Fellow Bill 
Bennett and Heritage Vice President <a href="/heritage/staff/vonkan.htm">John Von Kannon</a> spoke to 150 supporters 
and others at a luncheon in St. Louis, and Von Kannon addressed a meeting of 
Heritage members in Harbor Springs, MI.

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">W</FONT>indsor <FONT SIZE = "+2">S</FONT>ociety</H3></CENTER>

1994 saw continued growth in the Windsor Society, a special group of dedicated 
Heritage Members who contribute to the Heritage Foundation's long-range financial 
objectives through their estate plans or other planned gifts. In 1994, twenty-nine 
Heritage members made commitments to Heritage totaling more than $3.5 million. 
These generous gifts will ensure that there will always be a principled conservative 
institution in Washington fighting for free enterprise, limited government, 
traditional American values, and a strong national defense. 

In February 1994, the eighth meeting of the Windsor Society was held at the 
Biltmore Hotel in Scottsdale, AZ. The three-day conference focused on the crucial 
battle over health care that was unfolding in Washington. Heritage experts 
and more than 40 Heritage members discussed the importance of the health care 
debate in terms of America's future. Presentations on estate planning were 
also available to interested Heritage members, not only to support their deeply 
held conservative beliefs, but also to assist them and their families in their 
financial planning.  
<P>
The Windsor Society continues to help build the future financial support Heritage 
will need to continue fighting well into the 21st century for the values and 
principles which built America.

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">F</FONT>inancial <FONT SIZE = "+2">P</FONT>rofile</H3></CENTER>

Heritage's more than 200,000 individual, foundation, and corporate supporters 
in 1994 included:
<P>
30 Founders - donors of $100,000 or more, who provided Heritage with more 
than $6.9 million in contributions in 1994;
<P>
112 Associates - donors of at least $10,000 but less than $100,000, who provided 
$2.4 million in support in 1994;
<P>
282 members of the President's Club Executive Committee - donors of at least 
$2,500 but less than $10,000, who provided Heritage with $800,000 in 1994;
<P>
1,207 President's Club members - donors of $1,000 or more who  provided $1.2 
million.
<P>
Heritage's 5,100 Congress Watchers, $100 and above donors who help finance 
Heritage's U.S. Congress Assessment Project, provided some $500,000 in support 
in 1994, and Heritage's more than 200,000 individual members provided some 
$9.6 million.
<P>

<CENTER>

<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH =30%>
<H3>1994 Income</h3>
Individuals   50%<br>
