</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Transforming the Welfare Debate</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<h2>Transforming the Welfare Debate</h2>
<b>William J. Bennett & Peter Wehner</b></center>
<hr>
<p>
The welfare reform debate of the past two years will soon crystallize into a vote.  The Senate is scheduled to begin floor debate on a finalized welfare reform proposal in early August; the date for a final vote is not yet known.  Even less clear, however, is what that proposal will be. 
<p>
There are two competing Republican welfare reform plans under consideration.  The first, sponsored by Finance Committee Chairman Bob Packwood, has undergone several changes within the past month.  At this writing, it converts several welfare programs, including Aid to Families with Dependent Children (AFDC) into five separate block grants which would be turned over to the states, along with the responsibility of managing and administering poverty-fighting programs with this funding.  
<p>
Although it is a clear improvement over the current system, the Packwood bill has several significant shortcomings.  It promises devolution of resources and authority to state governments to enable them to enact innovative reforms.  But in reality, it saddles them with the most stifling and inflexible mandates in the current JOBS federal workfare program.   Even the Senate Democrats' welfare bill drops the JOBS program, which is widely regarded as heavily bureaucratized and ineffective.  Moreover, the Packwood bill places oversight of the states' use of block grants in the most bureaucratized agencies.  Most importantly, there are no serious measures to decrease illegitimacy, despite the obvious link between out-of-wedlock births and long-term welfare dependency.  
<p>
A competing bill was recently introduced by Senators Gramm, Ashcroft and Faircloth, and is rapidly gaining support. We consider this legislation, the "Work, Family and Community Welfare Reform Act," to be the best welfare reform legislation we have seen.  
<p>
The Gramm-Ashcroft-Faircloth bill is politically and intellectually significant, and it reflects the extraordinary shift that has taken place in the debate over welfare. It is significant that today nobody -- nobody -- is willing to defend the current welfare system.  And for good reason:  it is a complete wreck.  After thirty years, we have finally reached a consensus that much of the anti-poverty strategy of the 60's and 70's has been a terrible failure.  Poverty today is more widespread, more deeply entrenched and more pathological than it was three decades, and $5 trillion, ago. 
<p>
There are several important components of the Gramm-Ashcroft-Faircloth bill.    This legislation ends welfare as an entitlement and turns it over to the states, those "laboratories of democracy," to enable them to enact radical and innovative reforms, tailored to the needs and circumstances of their citizens.  It removes the meddlesome presence of the biggest federal bureaucracies from the administration of poverty programs.  It encourages adoption, one of the most important and overlooked issues in the realm of contemporary social policy.  And it recognizes that illegitimacy is the driving force behind welfare dependency, and takes steps to counteract the increase in out-of-wedlock births by ending cash payments to unwed teen mothers and eliminating the increase in cash handouts to welfare beneficiaries who have additional children out of wedlock.  
<p>
By the end of the decade, according to the most reliable projections, 40 percent of all American births and 80 percent of minority births will be out-of-wedlock.  These numbers have frightening social implications.  Welfare may not cause illegitimacy, but it does make it economically viable.  Welfare is illegitimacy's life-support system.
<p>
The good news is that we are reaching agreement on an important moral principle:  having children out-of-wedlock is wrong -- not simply economically unwise for the individuals involved, or a financial burden on society, but morally wrong.  The Gramm-Ashcroft-Faircloth bill is consistent with that principle.  
<p>
Another important component of this welfare bill would enable the states to contract with private institutions, including religious institutions, that run successful poverty-fighting programs.  In historian Marvin Olasky's exhaustive study of poverty-fighting in the United States, he concluded that the most effective poverty-fighting programs are those that are challenging, personal, and often, spiritual -- the exact antithesis of the bureaucratic, impersonal entitlement that is welfare "as we know it." 
<p>
Conservatives shouldn't pretend that welfare reform of this magnitude will not involve some dislocation and hardship.  But the current system -- designed, built and maintained by the architects of contemporary liberalism -- is exacting a far higher human cost.  Unless a principled and fundamentally different alternative is put into place, the body count will continue to rise.  So we have an obligation to act boldly and responsibly.
<p>
The Gramm-Ashcroft-Faircloth bill is far-reaching, intelligent and humane.  It is intelligent because it focuses on the underlying causes of long-term poverty and welfare dependency:  illegitimacy and family breakdown.  And it is humane because many more people will live far better lives by scrapping a failed system that subsidizes out-of-wedlock births.  The case for ending welfare is to promote policies which will help ameliorate the social pathologies and human misery that engulfs much of urban America.  The Gramm-Ashcroft-Faircloth bill will go a long way towards doing just that.  
<p>
There is one provision with which we do not agree:  denying assistance to legal immigrants, regardless of their circumstances.  We simply think that this is the wrong way to go.  But all things considered, this is still the best bill in the Senate.  It injects moral common sense into this debate.  
<p>
At this point the Gramm-Ashcroft-Faircloth legislation faces stiff opposition from some members of the Senate Republican Leadership (who favor Packwood's proposal) and Senate Democrats.  But its appeal is growing, as is its number of cosponsors.  Its passage would have several important consequences.  First, given its greater similarity to the welfare reform bill passed by the House of Representatives, the chances for achieving consensus with House delegates during the House-Senate conference will be far greater.  
<p>
Second, it will force President Clinton to make a clear choice.  There will be a lot of pressure for the President to make good on his promise to "end welfare as we know it" and sign the legislation.   If he vetoes it, he will have reneged on his promise, sabotaged the most significant welfare reforms in the American history, and perpetuated the status quo -- a political, if not a policy, victory for the Republican party.
<p>
Our current welfare system is the most pernicious set of government programs of the past three decades.  We have lost large parts of an entire generation because of the human wreckage left in its wake.  This bill will begin to undo some of the damage.  For that reason, we believe it merits support.
<p>
<hr>
William J. Bennett is a John M. Olin fellow at the Heritage Foundation and co-director of Empower America.  Peter Wehner is the director of  policy at Empower America.  
<p>
[ <a href="i-ps-lc.html">Policy Statements</a> | <a href="welcome.html">Home</a> ]

</body>
</html>
